.Dd February 10, 2026
.Dt EMIL 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm emil
.Nd text editor

.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Ar options
.Op Ar file

.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
provides editing of UTF-8 text files on VT100-compatible terminals.
Keyboard input controls cursor movement, text entry, and commands.
Multiple files may be open in buffers, with windows split for
simultaneous display.

.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It +N
Position the cursor at line number N when opening the file.
.It --version
Display version information.
.El

.Sh KEY BINDINGS
Key bindings largely follow Emacs conventions.
.Cm C-
denotes the Control key,
.Cm M-
denotes the Meta (Alt) key.
.Cm S-
denotes the Shift key.

.Ss Basic Commands
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-x C-c
Quit the editor.
.It Cm C-x C-f
Open a file and load it into a buffer.
.It Cm C-x C-s
Save the current buffer to its associated file.
.It Cm C-x k
Kill (close) the current buffer.
.It Cm C-x b
Switch current window to another buffer.
.It Cm C-x C-z
Suspend the editor to the background and return control to the shell.
.It Cm C-s
Interactive search in the current buffer.
.It Cm C-g
Cancel the current operation.
.El

.Ss Cursor Movement
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-n
Move cursor to next line.
.It Cm C-p
Move cursor to previous line.
.It Cm C-f
Move cursor forward.
.It Cm C-b
Move cursor backward.
.It Cm M-f
Move cursor forward by word.
.It Cm M-b
Move cursor backward by word.
.It Cm M-<
Move cursor to start of buffer.
.It Cm M->
Move cursor to end of buffer.
.It Cm C-a
Move cursor to beginning of line.
.It Cm C-e
Move cursor to end of line.
.It Cm F7
Scroll up one page.
.It Cm F8
Scroll down one page.
.It Cm C-UP
Scroll up one line.
.It Cm C-DOWN
Scroll down one line.
.El

.Ss Editing
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-_
Undo.
.It Cm C-x C-_
Redo.
.It Cm C-w
Kill (cut) region.
.It Cm M-w
Copy region.
.It Cm C-y
Yank (paste).
.It Cm C-k
Delete to end of line.
.It Cm C-u
Universal Prefix: Followed by a number it repeats the succeeding command.
.It Cm C-j
Insert newline without indenting.
.It Cm M-j
Insert newline and indent by inserting the same leading whitespace of the previous line.
.It Cm C-o
Insert newline without moving point.
.It Cm M-i
Insert 4 spaces.
.It Cm C-i
Insert a tab character.
.It Cm C-q
Insert next character verbatim.
.It Cm M-/
Completes the word at point, first using words from the current buffer, then all 
other buffers.
.El

.Ss Selecting Text
Regions are defined by setting a mark and moving the cursor. Once a
region is active, you can copy, cut, or manipulate the selected text.

.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-SPC
Set the mark at point to begin a selection.
.It Cm C-g
Cancel the mark (deactivates the current region).
.It Cm C-x h
Select the entire buffer (mark everything).
.El


.Ss Windows
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-x o
Switch to other window.
.It Cm C-x 0
Kill current window.
.It Cm C-x 1
Make current window the only window.
.It Cm C-x 2
Create a new window.
.El


.Ss Registers
Registers let you save the cursor position to return to later, like a bookmark. 
You can also save text regions, rectangles, numbers,
or keyboard macros. Each register is named by a single ASCII character.

.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-x r SPACE
Store a cursor positiom in a register.

.It Cm C-x r j a
Jump to the cursor position stored in register 'a'.

.It Cm C-x r a
Store a keyboard macro in a register.

.It Cm C-x r n
Store a number.

.It Cm C-x r s
Store a region in a register.

.It Cm C-x r +
Increment a number in a register, or append a region to a string.

.It Cm C-x r r
Copy a rectangle to a register.

.It Cm C-x r y
Yank a region or rectangle from a register.

.It Cm C-x r k
Kill a region or rectangle into a register.

.It Cm C-x r v
View contents of a register.
.El


.Ss Rectangles
Rectangles operate on column-aligned regions spanning multiple lines.

.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm C-x r t
Replace rectangle with string.
.It Cm C-x r k
Kill rectangle.
.It Cm C-x r y
Yank rectangle.
.El

.Ss Shell Integration
When enabled at compile time:

.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm M-|
Filter region through shell command.
.It Cm C-u M-|
Filter region through shell command and replace the region with the output. 
.El

.Ss Named Commands

.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm M-x
Enter a command by name.
.El


.Sh FILES AND ENCODING
.Nm
assumes all input and files is UTF-8 text.
It does not recognize or convert any other encoding.

.Nm
always loads files in their entirety into memory as a sequence of lines.
Lines are separated by a single linefeed and files terminate with a linefeed.

Null bytes (0x00) and invalid UTF-8 sequences may cause errors.

.Ss Saving Files
.Nm
writes the entire buffer to the associated file when saving. It attempts to do 
this atomically; if that is not possible, the option is presented of saving 
directly to the file, which can result in data loss if write fails. 
It does not create auto-save files.

.Sh UNDO HISTORY
.Nm
keeps a record of the last 1000 editing actions per buffer for undo and redo.

